- platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/analyze-site/index.ts

Context:
The 25-second sleep (around line equivalent to `await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, waitSeconds * 1000))`). The `finally` block closes the tab and disables network capture — but only after the sleep completes. If the MCP tool dispatch times out (DISPATCH_TIMEOUT_MS = 30s), the client gets an error at 30s, but the finally block doesn't run until up to 55s.

Fix for sleep: create a cancellable sleep using a manual cancel token:
```typescript
let cancelSleep: (() => void) | undefined;
const sleepPromise = new Promise<void>(resolve => {
  const timer = setTimeout(resolve, waitSeconds * 1_000);
  cancelSleep = () => { clearTimeout(timer); resolve(); };
});
await sleepPromise;
```
Then in the `finally` block, call `cancelSleep?.()` BEFORE the async cleanup operations so the sleep resolves immediately.

Fix for executeInTab: the current check (look for the exact line):
```typescript
if (typeof value === 'string' && value.length > 0 && (value[0] === '{' || value[0] === '[')) return null;
```
Change to: attempt JSON.parse and return the parsed value if it succeeds; return null only if parse throws (which indicates truncated/partial JSON):
```typescript
if (typeof value === 'string' && value.length > 0 && (value[0] === '{' || value[0] === '[')) {
  try {
    return JSON.parse(value);
  } catch {
    return null; // Truncated/partial JSON from Chrome
  }
}
```

Constraints:
- The cancelSleep must be called in the finally block BEFORE the async cleanup (closeTab, disableNetworkCapture) — ordering matters
- Do NOT change the overall structure of the analyze-site tool's try/finally pattern
- Read the full executeInTab function before making changes to understand all the value type handling paths

Files:
- platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/extension-get-logs.ts (NaN sort fix)
- platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/plugin-list-tabs.ts (hostnameFromPattern fix)

Context:
(1) extension-get-logs.ts — sort comparator:
```typescript
mergedEntries.sort((a, b) => b.timestamp - a.timestamp);
```
Fix:
```typescript
mergedEntries.sort((a, b) => {
  const at = typeof a.timestamp === 'number' ? a.timestamp : 0;
  const bt = typeof b.timestamp === 'number' ? b.timestamp : 0;
  return bt - at;
});
```

(2) plugin-list-tabs.ts — `hostnameFromPattern` current regex:
```typescript
const match = pattern.match(/^\*:\/\/([^/]+)\/\*$/);
```
This only matches `*://<host>/*`. Patterns like `https://localhost:3000/*` or `http://example.com/*` don't match.

Fix: expand the regex to match any scheme (or use URL parsing):
```typescript
const hostnameFromPattern = (pattern: string): string | undefined => {
  // Match *://<host>/* or <scheme>://<host>/* but not wildcard hosts like *.example.com
  const match = pattern.match(/^(?:\*|https?|wss?):[\/]{2}([^*/]+)\//);
  if (!match) return undefined;
  const host = match[1];
  // Skip wildcard hosts — can't uniquely identify an instance
  if (host.startsWith('*')) return undefined;
  return host;
};
```

Constraints:
- The hostnameFromPattern fix must NOT match wildcard hosts like `*.example.com` — those are not specific enough to identify an instance
- Keep the fix focused — do NOT change how the instance annotation loop uses the result
- `plugin-list-tabs.ts` also has `hostnameFromPattern` duplicated in `mcp-tool-dispatch.ts` (same logic) — check if there's a shared utility or if both need updating
